      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Hormones and the Menstrual Cycle</h5>
          
          <p>The menstrual cycle is regulated by a complex interplay of hormones that prepare the body for pregnancy each month.</p>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Key Hormones</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Estrogen</strong> - Primarily produced by the ovaries; responsible for developing and maintaining female sexual characteristics and reproductive system</li>
            <li><strong>Progesterone</strong> - Produced mainly by the corpus luteum after ovulation; prepares the uterine lining for implantation</li>
            <li><strong>Follicle-Stimulating Hormone (FSH)</strong> - Produced by the pituitary gland; stimulates the growth of ovarian follicles</li>
            <li><strong>Luteinizing Hormone (LH)</strong> - Produced by the pituitary gland; triggers ovulation</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Hormonal Changes Throughout Life</h6>
          <div class="table-responsive">
            <table class="table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Life Stage</th>
                  <th>Hormonal Changes</th>
                  <th>Effects</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Puberty</td>
                  <td>Rising estrogen and progesterone</td>
                  <td>Development of breasts, pubic hair, body fat changes, beginning of menstruation</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Reproductive Years</td>
                  <td>Cyclical changes in hormones</td>
                  <td>Regular menstrual cycles, fertility</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Perimenopause</td>
                  <td>Fluctuating hormones, declining estrogen</td>
                  <td>Irregular periods, hot flashes, mood changes</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Menopause</td>
                  <td>Significantly reduced estrogen and progesterone</td>
                  <td>End of menstruation, changes in bone density, skin, and vaginal tissue</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Sexual Health</h5>
          
          <p>Sexual health is an essential part of overall wellbeing and encompasses physical, emotional, mental, and social aspects of sexuality.</p>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Maintaining Sexual Health</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Regular Gynecological Exams</strong> - Important for early detection of issues and preventive care</li>
            <li><strong>Safe Sex Practices</strong> - Using barriers (condoms, dental dams) to reduce STI risk</li>
            <li><strong>Open Communication</strong> - Discussing boundaries, desires, and concerns with partners</li>
            <li><strong>Regular STI Testing</strong> - Important part of responsible sexual health</li>
            <li><strong>Understanding Consent</strong> - Ensuring all sexual activity is wanted and consensual</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Common Sexual Health Concerns</h6>
          <div class="accordion" id="sexualHealthAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingLibido">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseLibido" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseLibido">
                  Changes in Libido
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseLibido" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingLibido" data-bs-parent="#sexualHealthAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p>Fluctuations in sex drive are normal and can be influenced by many factors:</p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Hormonal changes (menstrual cycle, pregnancy, menopause)</li>
                    <li>Stress, fatigue, and psychological wellbeing</li>
                    <li>Relationship factors</li>
                    <li>Medications (including hormonal contraceptives and antidepressants)</li>
                    <li>Health conditions</li>
                  </ul>
                  <p>If changes in libido cause distress, speaking with a healthcare provider can help identify causes and solutions.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingPain">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapsePain" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapsePain">
                  Pain During Sex
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapsePain" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingPain" data-bs-parent="#sexualHealthAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p>Pain during sexual activity (dyspareunia) should not be ignored as it can signal an underlying issue:</p>
                  <ul>
                    <li><strong>Insufficient lubrication</strong> - Can occur due to hormonal changes, certain medications, or lack of arousal</li>
                    <li><strong>Vaginismus</strong> - Involuntary tightening of vaginal muscles</li>
                    <li><strong>Infections</strong> - Yeast infections, bacterial vaginosis, or STIs</li>
                    <li><strong>Endometriosis</strong> - Tissue similar to the uterine lining grows outside the uterus</li>
                    <li><strong>Pelvic inflammatory disease</strong> - Infection of reproductive organs</li>
                    <li><strong>Vulvodynia</strong> - Chronic pain or discomfort around the vaginal opening</li>
                  </ul>
                  <p>Consult with a healthcare provider to determine the cause and appropriate treatment. Don't suffer in silence.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingSTIs">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseSTIs" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseSTIs">
                  Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs)
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseSTIs" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingSTIs" data-bs-parent="#sexualHealthAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p>STIs are infections spread primarily through sexual contact. Many can be asymptomatic, making regular testing important.</p>
                  <p><strong>Common STIs include:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Human Papillomavirus (HPV)</li>
                    <li>Chlamydia</li>
                    <li>Gonorrhea</li>
                    <li>Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV)</li>
                    <li>Syphilis</li>
                    <li>Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV)</li>
                    <li>Trichomoniasis</li>
                  </ul>
                  <p><strong>Prevention:</strong></p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Consistent and correct use of barriers (condoms, dental dams)</li>
                    <li>Regular STI testing</li>
                    <li>Open communication with partners about sexual health</li>
                    <li>Vaccination (HPV, Hepatitis B)</li>
                    <li>Limiting number of sexual partners</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
