        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Recommended Screenings</h5>
          <p>Regular screenings are essential for maintaining reproductive health. Here are the recommended schedules:</p>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Pap Smear/HPV Test</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Ages 21-29:</strong> Pap test every 3 years</li>
            <li><strong>Ages 30-65:</strong> Pap test and HPV test every 5 years (preferred) OR Pap test alone every 3 years</li>
            <li><strong>After age 65:</strong> Can stop screening if history of normal results</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">STI Testing</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>All sexually active women:</strong> Annual chlamydia and gonorrhea screening recommended for ages 15-24</li>
            <li><strong>Higher risk individuals:</strong> More frequent testing for STIs including HIV</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">Breast Health</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Ages 20-39:</strong> Clinical breast exam every 1-3 years</li>
            <li><strong>Ages 40+:</strong> Annual mammogram and clinical breast exam</li>
            <li><strong>All ages:</strong> Monthly breast self-awareness</li>
          </ul>
          
          <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
            <p class="mb-0"><strong>Note:</strong> These are general guidelines. Your healthcare provider may recommend a different screening schedule based on your personal and family health history.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Sexual Health Myths vs. Facts</h5>
          
          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: You can't get pregnant during your period.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: While less likely, pregnancy can occur if you have sex during your period, especially if you have a shorter cycle or irregular periods.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: Birth control pills cause weight gain.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: Research suggests that most modern birth control pills don't cause significant weight gain. Individual responses vary, and some may experience water retention.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: You can't get an STI from oral sex.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: Several STIs, including herpes, gonorrhea, and syphilis, can be transmitted through oral sex.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: Douching helps keep the vagina clean and healthy.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: Douching can disrupt the natural balance of bacteria in the vagina, potentially leading to infections. The vagina is self-cleaning.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="myth-fact">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: Pap smears test for all STIs.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: Pap smears screen primarily for cervical cancer and HPV. Specific STI tests must be requested separately.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
